# Code Callouts with Two-Column Layout

When code blocks contain inline comments explaining the code, convert them to use AsciiDoc numbered callouts with a two-column slide layout.

## Format Structure

```asciidoc
[.slide.col-2]
== Slide Title

Introductory paragraph explaining what this code does.

[.col]
====
[source,cypher,role=noplay nocopy]
.Code block title
----
CODE HERE // <1>
MORE CODE // <2>
EVEN MORE // <3>
----
====

[.col]
====
<1> Explanation of first callout
<2> Explanation of second callout
<3> Explanation of third callout
====
```

## Conversion Rules

### 1. Slide Marker

Change `[.slide]` to `[.slide.col-2]`

### 2. Code Column

Wrap the code block in:

```asciidoc
[.col]
====
[source,language,role=noplay nocopy]
----
code here
----
====
```

### 3. Add Callouts

Replace inline comments with numbered callouts:

**Before:**

```cypher
MATCH (n:Node) // Find all nodes
RETURN n       // Return them
```

**After:**

```cypher
MATCH (n:Node) // <1>
RETURN n       // <2>
```

**Important:** Use only ONE callout per line. If multiple items on the same line need explanation, break them into separate lines or group the explanation.

### 4. Explanations Column

Add explanations in the second column with optional opening paragraph:

```asciidoc
[.col]
====
Optional paragraph providing context for the code block.

<1> Find all nodes with the Node label
<2> Return the matched nodes
====
```

The opening paragraph is optional but recommended when it helps the flow and provides useful context that would otherwise be redundant in each numbered explanation.

## Complete Example

**Before:**

```asciidoc
[.slide]
== Creating a Projection

Here's how to create a basic projection:

[source,cypher,role=noplay nocopy]
----
MATCH (s:Actor)-[r:ACTED_IN]->(t:Movie) // Match the pattern
WITH gds.graph.project(                 // Create projection
  'my-graph',                           // Name it
  s,                                    // Source nodes
  t                                     // Target nodes
) AS g
RETURN g.graphName, g.nodeCount         // Return stats
----
```

**After:**

```asciidoc
[.slide.col-2]
== Creating a Projection

Here's how to create a basic projection:

[.col]
====
[source,cypher,role=noplay nocopy]
----
MATCH (s:Actor)-[r:ACTED_IN]->(t:Movie) // <1>
WITH gds.graph.project( // <2>
  'my-graph', // <3>
  s, // <4>
  t // <5>
) AS g
RETURN g.graphName, g.nodeCount // <6>
----
====

[.col]
====
<1> Match Actors connected to Movies via ACTED_IN relationships
<2> Create a graph projection using the matched nodes
<3> Name the projection 'my-graph'
<4> Use Actor nodes as source
<5> Use Movie nodes as target
<6> Return the projection statistics
====
```

## Best Practices

- **One callout per line** - Never place multiple callouts on the same line
- Keep callout explanations concise (one line when possible)
- Use active voice in explanations
- Maintain the same level of technical detail as the original comments
- Add opening paragraph only when it adds value beyond what the numbered list provides
- Ensure callout numbers are sequential and match between code and explanations
